trans-unit.source: Edits metadata associated with columns in a dataset
trans-unit.target: Edits metadata associated with columns in a dataset

trans-unit.source: You can use the <ui>Metadata Editor</ui> module to change metadata that is associated with columns in a dataset.
trans-unit.target: You can use the <ui>Metadata Editor</ui> module to change metadata that is associated with columns in a dataset.

trans-unit.source: The data itself (including the values and the data types) are not actually altered—only the metadata inside Azure Machine Learning that tells downstream components how to use the column.
trans-unit.target: The data itself (including the values and the data types) are not actually altered—only the metadata inside Azure Machine Learning that tells downstream components how to use the column.

trans-unit.source: Treating Boolean or numeric columns as categorical values
trans-unit.target: Treating Boolean or numeric columns as categorical values

trans-unit.source: Indicating which column contains the <newTerm>class</newTerm> label, or the values you want to categorize or predict
trans-unit.target: Indicating which column contains the <newTerm>class</newTerm> label, or the values you want to categorize or predict

trans-unit.source: Changing date/time values to a numeric value
trans-unit.target: Changing date/time values to a numeric value

trans-unit.source: Use <ui>Metadata Editor</ui> any time you need to tweak the definition of a column.
trans-unit.target: Use <ui>Metadata Editor</ui> any time you need to tweak the definition of a column.

trans-unit.source: For example, some learners require specific data types.
trans-unit.target: For example, some learners require specific data types.

trans-unit.source: Other modules require specific flags on the columns, such as <languageKeyword>IsFeature</languageKeyword> or <languageKeyword>IsCategorical</languageKeyword>.
trans-unit.target: Other modules require specific flags on the columns, such as <languageKeyword>IsFeature</languageKeyword> or <languageKeyword>IsCategorical</languageKeyword>.

trans-unit.source: After performing the required operation, you can reset the metadata to its original state.
trans-unit.target: After performing the required operation, you can reset the metadata to its original state.

trans-unit.source: If you want to prevent changes to a particular metadata attribute, you can also select <ui>Unchanged</ui> from the drop-down menu or leave the new column name blank.
trans-unit.target: If you want to prevent changes to a particular metadata attribute, you can also select <ui>Unchanged</ui> from the drop-down menu or leave the new column name blank.

trans-unit.source: Use the Column Selector to choose columns by name, index, or type.
trans-unit.target: Use the Column Selector to choose columns by name, index, or type.

trans-unit.source: Note that you must apply the metadata change to all columns in the selection, so you might need to use multiple instances of <ui>Metadata Editor</ui> when mixing different types of transformations.
trans-unit.target: Note that you must apply the metadata change to all columns in the selection, so you might need to use multiple instances of <ui>Metadata Editor</ui> when mixing different types of transformations.

trans-unit.source: For example, if you are changing the data type of several numeric columns, you can select all the applicable columns, and then apply the change to all the columns.
trans-unit.target: For example, if you are changing the data type of several numeric columns, you can select all the applicable columns, and then apply the change to all the columns.

trans-unit.source: However, suppose you want to convert a numeric column to a categorical column, and at the same time, convert a different set of columns to features.
trans-unit.target: However, suppose you want to convert a numeric column to a categorical column, and at the same time, convert a different set of columns to features.

trans-unit.source: In that case, you would need to add a separate instance of <ui>Metadata Editor</ui>.
trans-unit.target: In that case, you would need to add a separate instance of <ui>Metadata Editor</ui>.

trans-unit.source: Specify the change that you want to apply to all the columns in the selection.
trans-unit.target: Specify the change that you want to apply to all the columns in the selection.

trans-unit.source: Specify how the column is to be used by machine learning tasks
trans-unit.target: Specify how the column is to be used by machine learning tasks

trans-unit.source: Use these parameters to modify the metadata of columns:
trans-unit.target: Use these parameters to modify the metadata of columns:

trans-unit.source: Use the <ui>Column Selector</ui> to select the columns to which your changes should apply.
trans-unit.target: Use the <ui>Column Selector</ui> to select the columns to which your changes should apply.

trans-unit.source: You can change the data type of the column if needed for specific operations.
trans-unit.target: You can change the data type of the column if needed for specific operations.

trans-unit.source: The data types supported are String, Integer, Float, Boolean, DateTime, and TimeSpan.
trans-unit.target: The data types supported are String, Integer, Float, Boolean, DateTime, and TimeSpan.

trans-unit.source: If you do not specify a new data type, the column metadata is unchanged.
trans-unit.target: If you do not specify a new data type, the column metadata is unchanged.

trans-unit.source: The change of data type occurs only in the metadata that is associated with the dataset.
trans-unit.target: The change of data type occurs only in the metadata that is associated with the dataset.

trans-unit.source: The actual column values are not altered unless you perform a different operation (such as rounding) on the column.
trans-unit.target: The actual column values are not altered unless you perform a different operation (such as rounding) on the column.

trans-unit.source: Also, you can recover the original data type at any time by using <ui>Metadata Editor</ui> to reset the column data type.
trans-unit.target: Also, you can recover the original data type at any time by using <ui>Metadata Editor</ui> to reset the column data type.

trans-unit.source: Use this option to specify that the values in the column be treated as categorical variables.
trans-unit.target: Use this option to specify that the values in the column be treated as categorical variables.

trans-unit.source: The actual data values are not changed, but machine learning algorithms will handle the data differently.
trans-unit.target: The actual data values are not changed, but machine learning algorithms will handle the data differently.

trans-unit.source: For example, numeric values will be treated as discrete, and they will not be used in calculations (such as calculating a mean value).
trans-unit.target: For example, numeric values will be treated as discrete, and they will not be used in calculations (such as calculating a mean value).

trans-unit.source: You can switch the metadata of the column back to the original type at any time by using another instance of <ui>Metadata Editor</ui>.
trans-unit.target: You can switch the metadata of the column back to the original type at any time by using another instance of <ui>Metadata Editor</ui>.

trans-unit.source: The metadata schema that is associated with each dataset consists of, at a minimum, the name and data type for each column.
trans-unit.target: The metadata schema that is associated with each dataset consists of, at a minimum, the name and data type for each column.

trans-unit.source: Whether the column contains a feature, a label, or a weight.
trans-unit.target: Whether the column contains a feature, a label, or a weight.

trans-unit.source: Whether the values in the column are numeric and can be used for computation or must be treated as discrete values (categorical variables).
trans-unit.target: Whether the values in the column are numeric and can be used for computation or must be treated as discrete values (categorical variables).

trans-unit.source: By default, all columns are initially treated as features.
trans-unit.target: By default, all columns are initially treated as features.

trans-unit.source: This means that when the dataset is used for training a model, the learning algorithm uses the values as inputs (independent variables).
trans-unit.target: This means that when the dataset is used for training a model, the learning algorithm uses the values as inputs (independent variables).

trans-unit.source: If the column contains the values that you want to predict, you should use <ui>Metadata Editor</ui> to change the field type to <ui>Label</ui>.
trans-unit.target: If the column contains the values that you want to predict, you should use <ui>Metadata Editor</ui> to change the field type to <ui>Label</ui>.

trans-unit.source: If the dataset has previously been used for other models, you might want to clear all previous metadata changes, by using the <ui>ClearFeatures</ui> or <ui>ClearLabels</ui> options.
trans-unit.target: If the dataset has previously been used for other models, you might want to clear all previous metadata changes, by using the <ui>ClearFeatures</ui> or <ui>ClearLabels</ui> options.

trans-unit.source: The ability to mark a column as a score is not available now, but will be added in a future release.
trans-unit.target: The ability to mark a column as a score is not available now, but will be added in a future release.

trans-unit.source: If you want to rename a column, type the new name.
trans-unit.target: If you want to rename a column, type the new name.

trans-unit.source: You can rename multiple columns, by typing the names as a comma-separated list in order of the column indices.
trans-unit.target: You can rename multiple columns, by typing the names as a comma-separated list in order of the column indices.

trans-unit.source: Note that column names can use only characters that are supported by the UTF-8 encoding.
trans-unit.target: Note that column names can use only characters that are supported by the UTF-8 encoding.
